{
  "thread_id": "first-proof-p8",
  "nodes": [
    {
      "id": "p8-problem",
      "node_type": "question",
      "post_id": 8,
      "body_text": "Polyhedral Lagrangian K in R^4, 4 faces per vertex. Does K have a Lagrangian smoothing?",
      "score": 0,
      "creation_date": "2026-02-11",
      "parent_post_id": null
    },
    {
      "id": "p8-s1",
      "node_type": "answer",
      "post_id": 801,
      "body_text": "Lambda(2) = U(2)/O(2), pi_1 = Z (Maslov class). Each face Lagrangian, edges are creases, vertices are multi-plane singularities.",
      "score": 0,
      "creation_date": "2026-02-11",
      "parent_post_id": 8
    },
    {
      "id": "p8-s2",
      "node_type": "answer",
      "post_id": 802,
      "body_text": "Edge-sharing: L_i = span(e_{i-1,i}, e_{i,i+1}). Lagrangian condition: omega(e_{i-1,i}, e_{i,i+1}) = 0 for each face. This kills 4 of 6 omega entries in edge basis.",
      "score": 0,
      "creation_date": "2026-02-11",
      "parent_post_id": 8
    },
    {
      "id": "p8-s3",
      "node_type": "answer",
      "post_id": 803,
      "body_text": "SYMPLECTIC DIRECT SUM: remaining omega entries are a=omega(e1,e3), b=omega(e2,e4). Vertex spanning lemma (proved): 4 edges must span R^4 for any topological submanifold (all Lagrangian planes in a hyperplane share a line => surface ruled => not compact submanifold of R^4). In basis (e1,e3,e2,e4), omega block diagonal. R^4 = V1 ⊕ V2.",
      "score": 0,
      "creation_date": "2026-02-11",
      "parent_post_id": 8
    },
    {
      "id": "p8-s4",
      "node_type": "answer",
      "post_id": 804,
      "body_text": "Each L_i = (line in V1) ⊕ (line in V2). Maslov loop decomposes: mu = mu1 + mu2. Each mu_j = winding number in RP^1. Both trace back-and-forth (not winding). mu = 0 exactly.",
      "score": 0,
      "creation_date": "2026-02-11",
      "parent_post_id": 8
    },
    {
      "id": "p8-s4a",
      "node_type": "answer",
      "post_id": 8041,
      "body_text": "Crease smoothing lemma (full local model): Darboux coords with edge along x_1-axis. L_i = graph of y=grad S_i for quadratic S_i. Interpolation S_eps = chi(x_1/eps)*S_1 + (1-chi(x_1/eps))*S_2. Graph of dS_eps is Lagrangian (exact 1-form). C^1 estimate: |grad(S_1-S_2)| = O(|x_2|) kills 1/eps singularity. V1⊕V2 persists under C^1-perturbation.",
      "score": 0,
      "creation_date": "2026-02-11",
      "parent_post_id": 8
    },
    {
      "id": "p8-s5",
      "node_type": "answer",
      "post_id": 805,
      "body_text": "Lagrangian surgery (Polterovich 1991): after crease smoothing (Sec 5a), sheets cross transversally with Maslov 0. Resolved by smooth neck. Darboux coords adapted to V1 ⊕ V2. Neck via generating function y = grad S(x).",
      "score": 0,
      "creation_date": "2026-02-11",
      "parent_post_id": 8
    },
    {
      "id": "p8-s6",
      "node_type": "answer",
      "post_id": 806,
      "body_text": "Global smoothing with support control: vertex surgeries in disjoint balls B_i (commute by disjoint support). Edge smoothings on remaining crease arcs. Composition of compactly supported Hamiltonian isotopies (McDuff-Salamon Prop 3.17). K_t -> K_0 in C^0.",
      "score": 0,
      "creation_date": "2026-02-11",
      "parent_post_id": 8
    },
    {
      "id": "p8-s7",
      "node_type": "answer",
      "post_id": 807,
      "body_text": "3-face impossible: 3 Lagrangian faces need omega=0 on all edge pairs (all adjacent = all pairs for 3). 3 isotropic vectors can't span 3D in R^4 (max isotropic dim = 2).",
      "score": 0,
      "creation_date": "2026-02-11",
      "parent_post_id": 8
    },
    {
      "id": "p8-c1",
      "node_type": "comment",
      "post_id": 8011,
      "body_text": "Numerical: 998/998 valid 4-valent configs give mu=0. Without edge-sharing, only 55% give mu=0. The constraint is essential, not generic.",
      "score": 0,
      "creation_date": "2026-02-11",
      "parent_post_id": 804
    }
